fields.title: Low Cost Solar Charge Controller
fields.content_1: For our fourth year in college (if I correctly remember) we had a mini project which was a solar charger which can track the movement of the sun across the sky. This thing uses a pair of light dependent resistors as sensors to determine whether the solar panels are facing the right direction. Then if the sensors voltage are not equal (as a consequence of not being in the right direction), then the DC motor connected to the axle of the solar panels will move forward or backward to move the solar panels to the direction facing the sun,
fields.content_2: Its also worth noting that the mechanical contraption we used was so primitive (and it works though) using a set of rubber bands, some baby powder containers and ball pen casings as axles. They were used to increase the torque capacity of the motor and also reduce the speed. During that time we did not have the capacity to build better mechanical parts so yeah.

fields.title: Automatic Power Management System
fields.content_1:
Three students from the Engineering and Technology Division (ETD) of Cor Jesu College was proclaimed champion in Design Project Competition under the Industrial and Biomedical Category during the 8th Engineering Congress held at University of Mindanao Professional Schools, Matina Campus, Matina, Davao City last March 11, 2016.

The winning entry was the research project of Ellen Jean V. Aclan, Jumarc V. Beltran, and Leslie S. Caminade.  The title of their research project was “Electrical Power Management with Mobile Text Messaging.”
fields.content_2: The congress was sponsored by the Council of Deans for Engineering Education (CODEE) XI in cooperation with the Commission on Higher Education Regional Office (CHED-RO) XI and Department of Science and Technology (DOST) Region XI.
fields.content_3: “It is a very good and useful project.  It can be commercialized which is applicable for big establishments or individual houses,” explained by Engr. Jonas M. Placer, the division chairperson of the Engineering and Technology Division (TED).   “Users of this device can monitor energy consumption and are guided in implementing an effective energy management,” he added.
fields.content_4: The congress was attended by students and professors from different schools in Region XI.  Engr. Jonathan B. Tungal, the students’ adviser, expressed his joy and appreciation to the efforts of the students in making such project with his guidance.

fields.title: DIY Voltmeter
fields.content_1: There was this one time in college we had this project that tries to imitate (horribly) the concept of a digital voltmeter. It uses a microcontroller that has an integrated analog-to-digital converter to measure a DC voltage and then simultaneously display it in a four-digit seven segment display. Building this was a challenge since we were faced with several challenges:
fields.content_2:
One of the ways to bring down the cost was to use a single microcontroller to do all the functions which is a) measure the DC voltage b) polling several buttons from a set of buttons c) display on a four-digit seven segment display on a limited set of pins.

Measuring the DC voltage part was easy. the microcontroller had a built-in ADC inside so this part just involved putting some code to activate that and calibrate that voltmeter.

Polling the buttons was a little bit harder. Because the microcontroller only supports single threaded operation, we had to spare a few cycles monitoring the inputs.

Displaying on the seven-segment was the most challenging. Directly driving all seven segments individually would require 7 x 4 pins and that is ridiculuous since we have only a limited set of output pins. (Around 8 to 10 were remaining after the buttons and the ADC input). We worked around that by utilizing time division multiplexing each seven segment display, meaning we would only flash one digit at a time, scanning through all the four digits fast enough that the human eye cannot perceive. This enabled us to share all the 7 pins to all the 4 seven segment displays.

The project was fun. If you wanna read more on how we did it, here are some links about the project.

fields.title: Review Lessons
fields.content_1:
I have been teaching review classes for years now in Complete Engineering Review and Training Center (CERTC) and if you are a student in the Philippines who needs to review for REE and ECE license exams then I highly recommend you enroll at us so that you can experience quality review and a very high chance of passing the board exams!

Review

I teach review lessons in all Electrical and Electronics subjects like Mathematics, Sciences, Electronics, and Communications subjects. This aims to recall all the concepts that may have been forgotten in the presumably at least 5 years of taking the degree of Electronics or Electrical engineeering. In this phase we throw concepts and problem solving techniques in a coherent way, very similar in how you would read a textbook
fields.content_2:
Preboard / Mockboard Exams

This is a phase where we test several things. One, we evaluate what have we retained from the review phase – which is quite a long one and then two, we also practice the processes involved in taking the actual board exam. This includes going to the venue, the outfit, the proper shading, time management, etc.
fields.content_3:
Refresher

In this phase we present to you a exam paper in which you have to solve for several hours. At the next day, we will discuss difficult parts of the exam and how to solve each problem. In this stage the problems tend to be varied. So the cycle of this phase tends to be; exam – ask – discuss – exam – ask – discuss.
fields.content_4:
Coaching

This is the most important part. We give you confidential materials (these tend to be not given out during the other phases) and then let you independently solve the exams. If it so happend that you really have difficulty answering the presented questions, we will be there to assist you, teach you the step by step solutions in the process of answering the questions. These are not lectures, but a one-by-one assistance on a case to case basis. Lectures can still be given if it so happens that a large enough number of students tend to have the same questions.
fields.content_5:
Board Exam

We will assist you in going to the venue, taking the boards, and we will wait for you outside the board exam venue while you are taking the board exam. Those who want to pray before the boards, we also assist in preparing the appropriate setting for you.

fields.title: Project Curious
fields.content_1:
The project started as an idea in September of 2018 when I noticed there are some multiple-choice-questions in my field of work that are very hard to find sources to. So I decided that if I have a handful of varied questions, I can create a software that can provide different variations of those questions.

This is the project during its infancy stage way back May 4, 2019. I just create this on my very little spare time so progress was slow. By this time note that also I am still learning Python (the computer language that I use) so I’m learning two things at the same time.
fields.content_2: For several months my works seemed to have no fruit. This was the time I was building my own classes, modules, and libraries and no actual code is having results. This was a frustrating portion of the development of this software.
fields.content_3: Currently, my work can now output results however only in text format. Next features that will be added might be automated formatting to docx files (I have pre-tested it, and it works) and also automation for creating larger textbooks for exercises.

fields.title: CERTC Online Review (Project CuriousWeb)
fields.content_1: The CuriousWeb project (which eventually became certconlinereview.com) is a website wherein students can access review problems used in PRC Engineer Licensure Exams. The questions here will be complete with answers and solutions. Another important thing is that the questions in the site are dynamically generated, and thus, in theory, no two questions will be exactly the same.
fields.content_2: By the time of writing, I am still developing the project. If you want to check out the site, you can click on this link. Update: The site became certconlinereview.com, of CERTC Review Center. In there students can go into lectures, take exams, answer different MCQs and problem solving question all done online. This was in consideration of the COVID-19 pandemic during the time of writing where face-to-face lectures are not an option. The online review enabled student to prevent the stagnation of knowledge by keeping their brains busy and trained about the board exam topics.
